How travel prices have changed since 1989
Until 1989 there were only 5 state travel agencies in Czechoslovakia: Cedok, Sporturist, CKM, Rekrea and Autotourist.
Travel agencies at that time offered travel mainly in the countries of the socialist bloc, as travel to the west was very limited.
Czech tourists traveled for holidays in East Germany, the Soviet Union (Sotchi, Crimea and the Black Sea), Bulgaria, Romania (both in the Black Sea) and Hungary (Balaton).
A great exception for the period 1962 to 1972 when it was allowed to travel to Yugoslavia and then the regime began to have a tendency for the west and the journeys to Yugoslavia were very limited for Czech tourists.
The great paradox of the socialist era was that it was not allowed for citizens of the socialist bloc (also for the Czechoslovaks) to travel individually even within the socialist countries.
In case the Czechoslovak citizen wanted to travel individually in Poland or the Soviet Union, for example, he needed an invitation letter if the individual travel was not allowed.
Travel agencies at that time also offered to travel to the West, however, it was necessary to row all night with a sleeping bag or have a "good knowledge" within the travel agency.
And even after that, it wasn't won yet.
The agreement for the currency that was the condition to travel west was denied to people "politically wrong" who could not travel at all.
However, the Czechoslovak currency was not interchangeable and it was not possible to obtain financial resources without the monetary agreement (western currency) to travel west.
The Czechs most often spent their vacations in the country where there were many country houses and chalets that the Czechs had bought, and this habit is still hard.
The journeys of the Czechs have been a major revolution since 1989.
Although holidays in East Germany and Bulgaria were maximum until 1989, the Czechs spent 4 million days abroad in countries around the world last year.
The great paradox that we are not aware of today is that the most popular country is Croatia, where it was not possible to go freely until 1989 because part of Yugoslavia of that time.
The abolition of visas in the 1990s in the neighbouring countries of the West caused a huge wave of short-term visits especially in Austria, Vienna and Germany.
The Czechoslovaks couldn't travel by plane west for a long time that everyone wanted to see for at least one moment.
For example, in Paris travel organizations made the Czechs sleep in tents in parks because our incomes did not allow us to pay the hotel or a pension.
The typical course of a Czech trip was at this time to bring with him his own food canned, sauce, etc.... to save.
Another important moment has also been the interchangeability of the Czech crown that finally allowed our tourists after decades of free access to Western currency.
Our standard of living, as well as the average wage, have increased what has caused another important moment around 1997.
With an increasing demand for travel, travel agencies have since 1997 begun to prepare tours with air charter connections that through contracts have greatly reduced costs compared to previous ones.
By the end of the 1990s, the Czechs had no visa-free links with almost most of the developed countries around the world outside the EU, which later facilitated our journeys.
Another interesting moment in the history of post-revolution tourism, when the first air charter was prepared for an exotic country, Thailand, from the Czech Republic.
Since this year, as every year of direct air charters, Czech tourists have been taking to distant warm countries; this winter there will be 12 exotic destinations from the Czech Republic.
More than 100000 Czechs visit exotic countries every year!
Another interesting moment in this period that symbolizes our post-revolution development came in 2008.
On 17 November 2008, the EU removed visas for Czech tourists and allowed our country to move fully into the group of developed countries.
Also in 2008 the Czechs for the first time in history spent more than half of their vacation abroad (50.3%) and for the first time in history spent more than 15,000 crowns per person for holidays abroad, including the attached charges.
