The low temperatures of February, apart from the loss of billions for the agricultural sector, limited the potential of the State economy for growth, led to a contraction of economic activity in general by 3.6 per cent in the first half of the year, mainly due to the decline of 31.16 per cent in agriculture, which affected the dynamism of other economic sectors.
According to the report on freezing by the Mexican Sustainable Rural Development Council, there were damage of 582 million 835 hectares cultivated, of which 78.03 per cent suffered total damage and the rest of 21.07 per cent suffered partial damage, the main affected crops were vegetables, maize and chic fish.
The decline in economic activity has generated, up to November, a steady increase in unemployment in the State, according to the National Institute of Statistics and Geography, the rate of unemployment of the State during the first three quarters of the year has been accelerated, as while from January to March 55 thousand 053 were unemployed, with a rate of 4.53 per cent of the Active Economic Population, in the second quarter the rate has become 5.28 per cent and from July to September the average continued to increase to 6.19 per cent, a rate of more than 74 thousand are unemployed, an increase compared to the first half of 18 thousand 969 people.
Less liquidity
Unemployment in Sinaloa during the year is multifactorial, according to economist Gerardo López Cervantes, director of the Faculty of Economic and Social Sciences of the AUS, the increase in unemployment can be explained indirectly in line with the actions carried out by public policy.
"What we see is an increase in unemployment that is due to various factors, including the loss of liquidity on the market due to a restriction of the resources approved by Congress to combat money laundering, because for people who earn dollars illegally it is not easy that they work for them, that they invest them and use them in something," he said.
Detained migration
López Cervantes reported that the increase in unemployment is also due to a demographic factor.
"The number of people leaving the State to work abroad has been restricted to the United States, firstly because of the difficulties of entry and secondly because they already have many difficulties in finding work, these people stay here and ask for work sources, which makes unemployment rising," he said.
Deficit
The analysis of the labour market in Sinaloa is compounded by considering the high level of serious lack that prevails among the working conditions, according to INEGI, 60.38 per cent of the population employed in this state work without contributing as a worker at any social insurance institution.
In addition to unemployment and serious lack of employment, another reason for the disbursement for the state is low wages, the entity has lower salaries in the country, according to the records of the Mexican Institute of Social Insurance and the Secretariat of Labour and Social Forecast.
By September, the average monthly income of workers was 5 thousand 352 pesos, much lower than the national average, which is 7 thousand 375 pesos.
IED contract
Apart from the decline in economic activity and the increase in unemployment, in 2011, the highest reduction in foreign direct investment over the last 10 years was recorded, according to the State's Economics Secretariat from January to June GDP reached $630,697, representing a decrease of 87.74 per cent compared to $5,143,312 recorded in the same period of the previous year.
In turn, the Government's Economic Development Secretariat accounts for a total investment of 17,280 billion pesos per year, mainly recorded by companies in the third sector.
Leave This
Given the economic contract scenario, the Government of the State requested in July the approval of a 3 billion-weight credit for investment in infrastructure projects in the 18 municipalities, with a view to revitalizing the economy, the approval of the State Congress was 2,600-billion-weight and until November no profit was observed from debt in any sector of the State economy.
Reactions
For representatives of the patron sector, the first year of the Government of Mario López Valdés showed a lack of Government management capacity.
Miguel Loredo López, president of the National Chamber of the Transformation Industry, said that there was no harmonization of the wills of the various sectors, including the Government of the State, in 2011.
"The performance of Sinaloa's economy during this year has been really very poor, it is necessary to work hard to recover the land that we lost this year, in 2012 we have to double our efforts, we have to align the effort of all and above all the good already synchronized walk of this new government team, we hope that next year will be much better," he said.
Economist
Loredo López stated that events such as early-year freezes have taken hold of the state's economy and have restricted its performance and growth.
"The low economic flow is produced from several events, including ice, one of the main effects has been a slow economy that does not turn fast enough to generate an economic dynamism that allows it to have an acceptable level of flow in the processes, products and services, and therefore, at the end of the year, we close much below the expectations we had," he said.
Redefine the vocation
For Teodoro Salazar Uriarte, President of the Mexican Confederation of Sinaloa, stated that the state is to be channelled towards more dynamic productive activities.
"In general terms, we have observed that we have worked, we believe that it is necessary to develop a long-term programme that redefines the vocation and economic direction of the State, because it is important to detonate all the potential of Sinaloa's material and human resources," he said.
A lot to do
The President of Coparmex stressed the importance of establishing a vision for the future that better channelled the Government's efforts.
"In general terms, I would say that the Government has made efforts to deliver good results in various areas, with regard to economic development progress, but it is important to develop a long-term programme," he said.
He noted that the current administration had shown progress in the management of public policy.
"There are elements that allow us to say that the Government is more inclusive, what I can say is that we have worked a lot and the Government is aware that there is still much to do," he said.
