The valid Court of Analogue Cutting in Mexico in 2015
The replacement of analogue signals by digitals is one of the most important changes that the world has suffered in recent years.
The Supreme Court of Justice of the Nation (SCJN) has raised the constitutional disputes raised by the Senate and the Chamber of Deputies against the presidential decree, which runs from 2021 to 2015, because the eight votes required for disabled persons were not gathered.
A minority of four ministers, including the President of the Court, Juan Silva Meza, considered that President Felipe Calderón did not exceed his duties when he issued the decree detailing the actions to be taken to implement the transition to digital terrestrial television.
As a result, the constitutional dispute promoted by the Senate of the Republic was raised for failure to reach the qualified majority of eight votes for the Court to decide on the constitutionality or non-constitutionality of the decree, and this remains in force.
The draft sentence, drawn up by Minister Olga Sánchez Cordero, proposed the declaration of the decree as non-constitutional, because the regulation on radio and television is a statutory assignment to the Federal Telecommunications Commission (Cofetel), in violation of the principles of hierarchical subordination and statutory reservation.
Only Zaldívar, Jorge Mario Pardo, Margarita Luna and Sánchez Cordero voted in favour of the project.
With this argument, both the Senate and the Chamber of Deputies have promoted two constitutional disputes to challenge the decree and, by admitting the complaints, Minister Sánchez Cordero has suspended the implementation of the decree and all the actions provided for by it for the digital transition.
The plenary meeting of the Ministers also resolved to address the complaint made by the Chamber of Deputies, without discussing the project to which Minister Sánchez Cordero is also responsible.
In his speech, the Minister said that he did not agree with the project's arguments, in that the Federal Executive could not structure through general standards the measures for the public administration to prepare for it.
"I do not consider it any more than if it were to affect the autonomy of the regulatory body," and he recalled that the planning of public policies in strategic areas such as the telecommunications sector is the responsibility of the Federal Executive, which has for constitutional mandate the government's management.
The replacement of analog signals by digital signals is one of the most important changes the world has ever experienced in recent years and this has resulted in better operation of the radio spectrum, better quality of the signal and more chains.
Admitting the change, he said, would be adjourning the benefits of digitisation, which involves a decision of public interest that does not only have a technical dimension, "because it also includes economic, social, political and national security issues".
He stressed that "the operation of an entire system requires, in accordance with the principle of economic direction of the State, a group of tasks which the Constitution grants to the State Executive's faculty."
He recalled that a large number of countries around the world had already completed the digital transition and had done so through the Executive, despite the fact that they had highly specialized technical bodies.
It cannot be concluded that the Executive, by issuing the contested decree, has infringed the sphere of competence of Congress in some way, as it ensures in the administrative sphere compliance with the laws issued by the Legislative.
An analysis of the possibility of a "vote by vote" discount in Michoacán
According to PREP, the difference between the first and second seats of the governor's election is only 27 per cent, even without accounting for the votes corresponding to 879 out of the 6 thousand 74 total records.
The option of the "voting by vote" discount is a reality with regard to the electoral process this year in Michoacán, where according to the preliminary Electoral Results Program (PREP) the difference between the first and second seats of the governor's election is only 27 per cent, even without accounting for the votes corresponding to 879 out of the 6 thousand 74 total records.
In this regard, the President of the General Council of the Michoacán Electoral Institute (IEM), María de los Ángeles Llanderal Zaragoza, recalled that a few days ago, last November 9, the electoral body approved a series of guidelines to harmonise local standards with federal electoral reform.
It will be recalled that Michoacán has not approved his Political Constitution or his Electoral Code of State or his Electoral Justice Act, while at the same time the Congress of State approved the reforms shortly before the legal deadline for this electoral process to enter into force, and Governor Lionel Godoy Rangel has omitted its publication within the time limits provided for by the Official Journal of the State Act, arguing that he had some objections.
On 9 November, the Supreme Court of Justice of the Nation (SCJN) resolved the constitutional dispute promoted by the local Legislative Power and described the vote of the State Secretary for Constitutional Reform as "inappropriate and illegal" because he did not have the right to "sanction or challenge them".
Interviewed on the possibility of "voting by vote", María de los Ángeles Llanderal stated that with the approval of the relevant guidelines by the General Council of EMI, it would be possible to make partial and total savings of the votes by the local electoral body.
Thus, the partial downturn of votes, one or more electoral packages, may be that: the results of the minutes do not coincide; there is no record of voting and there is no record of voting in the urn file at the chairman of the hearing; or there are obvious errors or changes in the records.
In addition, the total deduction of the votes received in all polls can be made when there is an indication that the difference between the alleged candidate in the respective election and the candidate in the second ballot is equal to or below a percentage point; provided that at the beginning of the session there is an express request from the representative of the party and/or coalition who has submitted the second of the candidates reported.
The total savings of the ballot may also be made if at the end of the common disbursement it follows that the difference between the proposed candidate winning and that of second place is equal to or less than a percentage point, provided that there is an express request from the representative of the political party to which the candidate is seconded, in which case the electoral packages which have been the subject of the partial disbursement will be excluded.
It should be noted that this is the situation of Morelia's election, where according to the PRESS, the difference between the first and second places is only 0.16 per cent, even without accounting for the votes of 129 of the 923 total verbatim records.
