"Going to Costa Rica is a dream that has become a reality"
In the exclusive interview with Viva, bassist Jeff Ament from Pearl Jam said the group is ready to offer one of its best concerts next Sunday at the National Stadium.
They have been waiting for more than 20 years, but the group ensures that this will also become a dream to happen in this country.
It is that the bassist and founder member Jeff Ament assured, speaking exclusively with Viva, from Brazil, last week.
The group is located in the South American wing of its two-decade celebration tour and Sunday 20 will take its only step in Central America.
This day will be presented at the National Stadium, beginning at 7:30 p.m., next to the Los Angeles The X group and the Las Robertas Nationals.
This is an extract from the conversation, whose full transcription is in La Nación on the Internet.
For his Costa Rican fans, the fact that Pearl Jam will take place in Costa Rica is a dream that has become a reality. Are you aware of what your fans are living?
Going to Costa Rica is a dream that has become a reality for us too.
This is our second time in South and Central America and so far it has been great.
I only spent my vacations in Costa Rica; it's such a beautiful country and I think we can spend a few days there.
So we're excited to bring our music there.
I ask you, because there is a kind of devotion to the group, the fans live intensively the previous days.
What is your message for your most keen fans?
Thank you for staying with us all these years.
It took 21 years for us to get to Costa Rica; thank you for waiting so long and we're sorry that so much time had to go by.
Some people already say that his concert is the biggest show of the year.
Does this add some pressure to your visit?
Some of the biggest shows we've offered over the past 21 years have taken place in the last two weeks.
We offered two giant shows in Sao Paolo and we hope that this has shaped us for this concert in Costa Rica.
We are really very impatient to produce it.
We love this country, we love surfing and jungle; for both things, Costa Rica is one of the best countries in the world.
How did you discover Costa Rica and its surfing waves?
We have a lot of surfing friends and I have a very good friend who lives in Tamarindo and the waves are incredible there.
My friends were always going to surf in Costa Rica and Nicaragua, next to Mexico, are great places to surf; that's how we learned it, through people who love surfing.
Seeing the tour, you offered huge shows, with a lot of songs.
What have you planned for your presentation in Costa Rica?
Since we have never been produced there, we have no restrictions on what we can do.
We will try to do the best possible show, with a wide variety of songs; we will try to interpret two songs from each album and offer our fans a good and diverse directory.
You never repeat the directory.
What's that all about?
I think it's partly because we have nine CDs and we can interpret more than 120 songs and each love different songs, so it's very difficult to choose which songs to interpret every evening.
When we have two or three songs in the directory that we have not interpreted for a long time, it helps us to stay focused and surprise us because it reminds us of the reasons why we love these songs and that we may have forgotten them.
This makes the show more interesting for us and, therefore, I think it also becomes more interesting for people.
With this tour, you will celebrate 20 years of travel.
Looking back, is it hard to believe everything you've done?
Yes, absolutely.
First of all, I think none of us had imagined that we were going to form a large rock group, and the fact that we did it for more than 20 years makes it seem like a dream.
We continue to tell of our blessings and the fact that we can continue to make music together makes us very excited.
We love and love to create music.
We're lucky to go to places in the world we've always wanted to go to.
Things couldn't go any better for us.
What does it mean for you to have been a fundamental element in the creation of the earth?
It has always been an honor for us to be part of this large group.
We are very friends with the people of Soundgarden, Mudhoney and Alice in Chains.
It's surprising when a movement comes from a group of friends and it's not common.
From time to time, a group emerges from a city, but it is much more strange when five or ten groups come out of the same city at the same time.
We are proud and it is an honor for us to be part of the Seattle Group.
We still play with some of them from time to time.
Last year we participated in a festival with Alice in Chains and we went to Canada with Mudhoney, we saw in Soundgarden in their tour, so we are lucky to be still friends with them all and it is an honor for us to be part of this sound from Seattle that emerged.
It is as strange that a group like yours remains united and with the same members for so long.
Yes, four of us have been together for 21 years and Matt (Cameron) joined us 13 years ago, and this is only much longer than many groups normally last.
First of all, I believe that we are all lucky to be still alive and, secondly, we are all concerned about others.
We are all intimate friends and thanks to this there are musical boulevards that give everyone the freedom to experience.
We have confidence in each other with each other's music and that could not be better.
Your relationship with the word celebrity has not been easy; however, thanks to your success, you have been able to do whatever you want.
How do you find a balance?
As we grew up, it was easier for us to find a balance.
We make sure that we don't spend too much time on tour because it's easy to fall into this game of great crowds and people who love your music.
If we do not forget that people are there for music, it helps us not to forget that we must respect music and what it has brought, without taking into account the fact that we are famous and a rock star, which does not really interest any of us.
How do you remember your other project, Mother Love Bone?
