UNAM asphalt would avoid cassis
Rafael Herrera, a researcher at UNAM Faculty of Chemistry, develops modified asphalts with polymers to produce a mixture with better performance, regardless of environmental and temperature conditions.
If the paving signals were resolved, it would no longer be necessary to repair about 200 thousand cases each rainy season in the Metropolitan Zone of the Valley of Mexico, warned Rafael Herrera Nájera, a UNAM Faculty of Chemistry (FQ) researcher, who ensured that if the building and maintenance of the bituminous paving process is adequate, the cases could be reduced or even completely eliminated.
During his conference A technological opinion on the case, organized within the framework of the International Year of Chemistry, he announced that the laboratory he is responsible for develops modified asphalts with polymers to produce a mixture with characteristics similar to those of the asphalt, but with greater mechanical resistance, both high and low temperatures.
Herrera Nájera considered that this type of modified asphalt could be used in places where the climate is extremely hot, like some cities in the north of the country, to improve performance, and therefore case formation.
He explained that the asphalt, the heavier part of the oil, is a set of hydrocarbons molecules, molecules with a heavier molecular weight, called asphaltenes, and molecules with a low molecular weight, called malthenes, which together give the peacock its characteristic viscoelastic behavior.
The viscoelastic behavior of the asphalt consists in the fact that at high temperatures, almost 180 degrees, behaves as a liquid, at 120 degrees C its viscosity is very large and at 50 degrees C it has an almost solid state, while at very low temperatures, the asphalt becomes breaking, it adds.
This means that in the streets the resistance of the asphalt is not uniform and changes during the day depending on the environmental and temperature conditions, the chemical engineer warns.
The FQ researcher observed that the streets of Ciudad in Mexico were mostly covered by a flexible floor, consisting of six layers of materials, the last three of which involve asphalt.
Among the most surface layers is the asphalt layer, made up of small stones bathed in asphalt and compacted later.
Each of the small stones that form the layer, it signals, is bathed an asphalt.
When vehicles pass through it by generating efforts, it allows the forces to spread very well in the floor.
If the asphalt had been modified, it would have spread better to the chemical engineer.
On the asphalt layer, he says, we put a last layer called the asphalt layer, made of fine stone, that is, of sand which is also bathed in asphalt.
As this layer is in contact with the wheels of the vehicles, it must have more mechanical strength than the asphalt layer and provide access to the street.
As part of the floor that receives and distributes the effort, the rolling layer also requires that it has adequate thickness and the material it is made must be maintained.
The climate, especially the humidity and temperature changes, is also a very important factor to consider, especially water, because they significantly affect the performance of the asphalt layer.
When the soil wets, the water spreads within the layer it is difficult for the soil to form, which refills all layers of the floor and therefore causes cassis.
In the process of forming a case, he said, the first that is missing is the motion film and only later the asphalt layer is affected, but the damage does not take place immediately, but it is a process that must be treated to the first signals with adequate maintenance programs.
The member of the National System of Researchers explained that vehicle loading is another important factor for case formation and therefore the thickness of each layer of the floor must always be linked to vehicle loading and ensure its satisfaction, in order to avoid frequent case formation.
Rafael Herrera has warned that there is still much to investigate and work on asphalt, for example, bituminous emulsions, which exist in other countries already on the market and allow for the repair of cases easily and without having to use high temperatures.
