We need to legalize euthanasia and assisted suicide, a committee of experts says
Canadians live in the denial of death, according to the report of the Royal Society of Canada
In the field of palliative care, the Committee demands that governments, health care institutions and doctors work together to ensure better palliative care, and so on, in addition to cancer.
Canadian society lives in the denial of death.
Only 9% of Canadians agree to talk to their doctor about the conditions under which they want to die and make arrangements to do so.
This is one of the conclusions of an impressive report by the Royal Society of Canada, involving six experts in various fields, including ethics, law and medicine.
The Committee recommends that the Government amend the Criminal Code so as to allow the assisted suicide and euthanasia, when necessary, to a patient considered competent to make such a decision.
At the start of the game, experts cite a recent survey of the United Intelligence Economist, who compared the quality of death in 40 countries on the planet.
If Canada ranks 10th, the study notes that "the medicalization of death in Canada has created a culture in which people are afraid of dealing with the subject of death".
Medicalization or not, 77% of Canadians do not have access to palliative care, we are told by the experts mandated by the Royal Society of Canada.
And despite the desire of most Canadians to die at home, 68.6% of them end up dying at the hospital.
Overall, in Quebec, this rate is the highest, with 86% of the deaths occurring in the hospital.
On the sensitive issue of euthanasia and assisted suicide, the authors of the report come to conclusions that go against the position of the federal government, which has already said they want nothing to change to the Criminal Code on euthanasia and assisted suicide.
However, according to experts, who have also reviewed all countries where these approaches are legalized or decriminalized, there is no evidence that such decriminalization leads to abuse in the application, i.e. the practice of euthanasia or suicide in persons who are not competent or consenting.
On the contrary, Jocelyn Downie, co-sponsor of the report, said yesterday at a teleconference, there would be more cases of these floods precisely in countries where euthanasia and assisted suicide are not legalized.
"Euthanasia is practiced in Canada, where it is clearly illegal."
"The assisted suicide is practiced in Canada, where it is clearly illegal," explains Jocelyn Downie.
Canadians in favour of euthanasia
We recall that 85% of Canadians have already spoken for euthanasia because they believe it will allow people to live to ease their suffering, according to an Angus Reid survey conducted in 2010.
And 66% believe that legalizing euthanasia will not have the effect of sending the message that the life of the elderly or the disabled is less valuable.
In the case of persons who have committed suicide, the investigators believe that they should not be prosecuted.
With regard to the maintenance or termination of care in a patient, the situation is less clear, the authors of the report say.
Thus, in the list of their recommendations, they suggest that it is indicated in the Criminal Code that the withdrawal of care for which there was a legally valid refusal is not a criminal.
The Committee of Experts also requests that health professionals be trained to respect a refusal of care at the end of life, without fear of criminal prosecution.
In the field of palliative care, the Committee demands that governments, health care institutions and doctors work together to ensure better palliative care, and so on, in addition to cancer.
Finally, with regard to palliative or terminal sedation, which has already been widely used in Canadian health institutions, the Committee requests that it be considered, if it is not used to reduce physical pain, such as euthanasia, and that it be subject to the same procedures.
Reserves of other experts
