The North Stream, new gateway to Russian gas in Europe
The North Stream pipeline, directly connecting Western Europe to Russia through the bottom of the Baltic Sea, has entered into service.
It must provide gas for the equivalent of 30 million households.
Gazprom, the Russian gas giant, wanted to celebrate the event with excitement.
More than 500 guests, including four heads of state and government, took part on Tuesday on the shores of the Baltics, between the final orchestra and buffet, at the inauguration of the North Stream, this new pipeline that directly connects Russia to Germany under the sea.
Symbolically, German Chancellor Angela Merkel, Russian President Dmitri Medvedev, French Prime Minister François Fillon and his counterpart from the Netherlands Mark Rutte turned together the valve steering the entry of Russian gas into the Western European network.
With this new pipeline, 27.5 billion cubic metres of additional Russian gas will arrive every year in Western Europe by a first tube of 1,224 km connecting the Saint Petersburg region to the Land of Mecklenburg-Pomérania.
A second tube must be completed at the end of 2012, allowing to deliver a total of 55 billion cubic meters of gas, the equivalent of all French consumption.
And we are already talking about the possibility of building a third on the same path.
For Gazprom, the completion of this huge building in time and time has a victory air.
The project had been strongly contested by Poland and the Baltic States.
The North Stream will be able to deliver gas directly to Germany, avoiding any land transit through a third country (Poland or Ukraine).
Suddenly, these two countries lose some of their power: it becomes more difficult for them to weigh on Russia by threatening to shut it down to Western European markets.
In the strongest of the debate, Warsaw had not hesitated to compare the North Stream to a "new German-Soviet pact", referring to the alliance between Hitler and Stalin to occupy Poland in 1939.
That is whether the subject is politically sensitive.
Western Europe, with its support for this Russian project, has gained greater security of supply.
But it is at the price of weakening Europe's energy, as the project has created a gap between Eastern and Western Europeans.
In five years' time, Russia knew how to triumph over its vision of a direct alliance between Russia and the rich western countries, heavily gas-consumers, and whose deposits are in decline.
"This pipeline is an integral part of our partnership with Russia, it is a new artery that connects us organically," said François Fillon, inaugurating this pipeline, demonstrating the extent to which large gas contracts are both political and economic.
All this explains the broad smiles shown by the leaders of Gazprom, who are present in number in Lubmin, at the point of arrival of the gas.
The construction of this pipeline is also a technical operation.
The submarine tube is made of concrete steel to protect it from the anchors of the ships.
It is based on the bottom of the sea, 200 m on average.
To build it, it was necessary to avoid land mines dating back to World War II.
"A hundred had to be removed or destroyed with caution," says Jens Müller, spokesperson for North Stream.
The measures to protect the fauna and flora have also had to be multiplied.
The tube is a long metal snake, heavy as 242 Eiffel towers, which nothing interrupts all its length: neither valve nor maintenance station.
A control platform was planned outside Sweden, but those responsible for the project gave up while the Swedish people were reluctant to see a Russian state company established permanently outside their coasts.
"In the event of an accident, we stop the gas transition in less than a minute," says Jens Müller.
In case of escape, the gas contained in the gas pipeline therefore escapes into the air.
But this case is considered unlikely by the manufacturers who planned the wetlands to flee every 100,000 years.
The monitoring of the state of the pipeline is ensured by a submarine robot, trained by a ship for external observation, as well as by a device operating inside the pipeline.
From the shape of a cigarette, it is inserted inside the tube, a diameter of one metre, and it is pushed by the gas.
On arrival, after three full days of 3 m2 trip, he provides specific information on possible metal deformations.
The pipeline was designed to operate for 50 years without having to make the least repair.
Gas flow is simply ensured by the pressure.
It is 200 bars away, and 100 at arrival.
Five companies have joined forces to implement this project.
The leader remains Gazprom, which holds 51% of the stakes.
Germans E.ON and BASF (15.5% each), as well as the Dutch Gasunia and the French group GDF Suez (9% each) joined.
These five companies have created a joint venture called Nord Stream, which is responsible for building and operating the pipeline.
It has its seat in Zug, Switzerland, where taxation is particularly favourable.
Gazprom then hired this company, for twenty years renewables, the total capacity of gas transport.
" Gazprom will pay for the total capacity, whatever the amount of gas actually transported," explains Jens Müller.
The financing of the construction of the pipeline was secured by shareholders at 30% and by 70% by bank loans.
The total cost of the work should be €7.4 billion for both tubes.
For GDF Suez, for example, the investment amounted to 240 million.
But minority shareholders are sure to get back to their costs, as only Gazprom takes the risk.
The gas pipeline emerges from the Baltic to Lubmin, on a sandy shoreline planted with pine trees.
Valves, 4.5 meters high, form the gas output door.
Sensors measure the pressure, temperature and specificities of the gas that reaches before it is transferred to the German gas pipelines.
Since last Tuesday, this terminal has received a million cubic metres of Russian gas every hour.
With full capacity, it will be 3 million per hour and in 2012, 6 million.
